I really enjoyed this question, so I want to start with this one from Lake Watkins.

21
00:01:36,217 --> 00:01:38,679
Lake Watson says, Hi Kerry, thanks for the AMA.

22
00:01:39,039 --> 00:01:43,901
They are curious what tools or techniques you use for player modeling in your games.

23
00:01:44,261 --> 00:01:46,983
Do you identify player psychographics or use some other approach?

24
00:01:47,003 --> 00:01:49,484
I actually knew Obsidian has a decent model for this, so I was

25
00:01:49,844 --> 00:01:52,665
I wanted to throw this one up top because it was pretty sophisticated.

26
00:01:53,506 --> 00:01:56,067
By which you mean like who we think the player

27
00:01:56,327 --> 00:01:58,508
who we think the player is trying to play in the game?

28
00:01:58,959 --> 00:02:03,462
I think identifying different player types, you know, like explorers, story nerds, combat nerds,

29
00:02:03,502 --> 00:02:06,783
like that's a very shorthand rough example I would use, but yeah, I think that's where the

30
00:02:06,803 --> 00:02:12,427
question is going. Yeah, so for that I think the first question is what kind of game are you making

31
00:02:12,547 --> 00:02:17,069
and what are the fundamental design pillars of that game, you know, and that is sort of the

32
00:02:17,149 --> 00:02:22,112
first filter for, you know, what kind of player base, what kind of player type you're really

33
00:02:22,172 --> 00:02:22,872
trying to serve.

34
00:02:24,299 --> 00:02:27,521
You know, for a lot of the games, like, we're mostly known for RPGs,

35
00:02:28,042 --> 00:02:31,184
with a lot of story and a lot of reactivity and a lot of player freedom.

36
00:02:31,985 --> 00:02:36,948
So, our model for a lot of those types of games is a lot of tabletop role-playing games.

37
00:02:37,509 --> 00:02:40,010
So, you know, we try to...

38
00:02:40,811 --> 00:02:43,173
we look at the things that players seem to get the most out of that,

39
00:02:43,213 --> 00:02:46,135
like they get a lot of character interaction.

40
00:02:46,615 --> 00:02:49,577
They get the sense of a really big reactive world to explore

41
00:02:49,617 --> 00:02:51,999
that gives them lots of options for how to solve problems.

42
00:02:52,723 --> 00:02:54,365
Lots of tools that they can use.

43
00:02:55,887 --> 00:02:58,591
And again, a high degree of reactivity to how they use those tools.

44
00:02:59,552 --> 00:03:01,795
Meaningful and interesting characters to interact with.

45
00:03:02,076 --> 00:03:03,237
So I think a lot of the...

46
00:03:04,175 --> 00:03:07,717
The player types we assume like we know there are people who want to go fight things.

47
00:03:07,877 --> 00:03:12,520
We know there are players who want to explore and immerse themselves in a really deep, well-realized

48
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:13,140
reactive world.

49
00:03:13,200 --> 00:03:16,763
And we know there are players who really care about story and character and companions.

50
00:03:16,923 --> 00:03:19,825
And they want to get to know everybody in the world, talk to everybody.

51
00:03:20,625 --> 00:03:27,289
So you know, knowing that those are I think kind of the three, the three big content draws

52
00:03:27,329 --> 00:03:27,890
of our games.

53
00:03:28,616 --> 00:03:34,000
We try to set them up in such a way that players can approach that content in whatever way

54
00:03:34,060 --> 00:03:35,541
and with whatever focus we want.

55
00:03:35,661 --> 00:03:36,482
Tremaine Williams.

56
00:03:36,522 --> 00:03:38,483
Tremaine, thank you so much for hanging out with the Showcase.

57
00:03:38,523 --> 00:03:40,584
I've seen you in a bunch of chats, just wanted to give you a shout out.

58
00:03:41,125 --> 00:03:45,008
Tremaine Williams wants to know, when building an open world game, how do you determine how

59
00:03:45,448 --> 00:03:46,309
big is too big?

60
00:03:46,329 --> 00:03:48,690
How do you deal with dead space between points of interest?

61
00:03:49,420 --> 00:03:49,720
Oh, man.

62
00:03:49,740 --> 00:03:52,822
I mean, there are a lot of ways we can do this.

63
00:03:53,022 --> 00:03:57,445
It's, you know, obviously an interesting environment for the player to traverse,

64
00:03:57,945 --> 00:04:01,648
you know, combat encounters in between banter with your companions,

65
00:04:02,608 --> 00:04:05,290
you know, but sometimes a little bit of dead space is OK.

66
00:04:05,510 --> 00:04:08,732
Like if the player is always moving from one encounter to the next,

67
00:04:08,892 --> 00:04:10,593
you know, from one bit of banter to the next,

68
00:04:11,594 --> 00:04:15,476
there's not really a moment to just sort of slow down and appreciate.

69
00:04:15,617 --> 00:04:17,438
And also anticipate where you're headed.

70
00:04:19,288 --> 00:04:24,651
And I think this is where just like playtesting and again, understanding like what is the

71
00:04:24,671 --> 00:04:28,353
pace of the experience you're trying to offer is really important.

72
00:04:28,373 --> 00:04:30,754
Because again, you do want a little bit of quiet space.

73
00:04:31,394 --> 00:04:35,796
Some of the most fun I've had in The Witcher 3 and in games like Breath of the Wild is

74
00:04:35,836 --> 00:04:39,358
just sort of getting from one point to the next and kind of having this goal in mind

75
00:04:39,418 --> 00:04:41,639
of I see something in the distance, I want to get there.

76
00:04:41,659 --> 00:04:43,380
And I know it's going to take me a little bit of time to get there and I'll run into

77
00:04:43,400 --> 00:04:43,720
a few surprises.

78
00:04:43,740 --> 00:04:44,501
But I'm going to keep trying.

79
00:04:44,521 --> 00:04:45,061
I'm going to keep running.

80
00:04:45,081 --> 00:04:45,601
So, thank you for watching.

81
00:04:45,621 --> 00:04:46,281
And I'll see you in the next one.

82
00:04:46,301 --> 00:04:46,442
Bye.

83
00:04:46,947 --> 00:04:50,229
Because I am interested in this world and I don't know what I'm going to find next,

84
00:04:50,569 --> 00:04:52,190
the process of getting there is fun.

85
00:04:53,631 --> 00:04:54,051
Right on.

86
00:04:54,171 --> 00:04:56,973
Our next question comes from Katie Setoff.

87
00:04:57,374 --> 00:05:00,556
Katie would like to know, as a narrative designer, do you ever run into trade-offs

88
00:05:00,596 --> 00:05:02,737
between storytelling and engineering limitations?

89
00:05:02,877 --> 00:05:04,638
If so, how do you balance those concerns?

90
00:05:05,779 --> 00:05:09,022
Yeah, I mean, I think engineering limitations,

91
00:05:09,462 --> 00:05:13,325
I think that's an issue for just about every design department.

92
00:05:14,146 --> 00:05:16,308
And fundamentally, I think you do

93
00:05:16,348 --> 00:05:19,350
have to start from the perspective of what is possible

94
00:05:19,490 --> 00:05:23,173
and what are the tools I have at my disposal

95
00:05:23,233 --> 00:05:25,275
and what are the constraints that I have to abide by,

96
00:05:26,076 --> 00:05:28,558
rather than saying, let me just do what I want

97
00:05:28,618 --> 00:05:30,799
and make it someone else's problem to make it work.

98
00:05:32,461 --> 00:05:33,041
So I mean, again,

99
00:05:34,820 --> 00:05:39,621
This can relate to how often or how many cutscenes you can use,

100
00:05:40,301 --> 00:05:43,162
you know, sort of the graphical fidelity of conversations.

101
00:05:44,723 --> 00:05:48,144
And I mean, honestly, there are a lot of gameplay constraints as well that play into this. Like,

102
00:05:48,444 --> 00:05:52,865
are you playing a game where you can kill every NPC? Because if so, that's something that you

103
00:05:52,905 --> 00:05:57,407
have to adjust for in the way you tell stories and the alternate avenues you offer to players.

104
00:05:58,287 --> 00:06:01,388
Is this a game where we are going to automatically pull players into

105
00:06:01,945 --> 00:06:17,844
Any conversation they encounter or do we allow players to opt in again, in which case, you know, you have to have to think about how those players are going to get have a good experience, even if it's not necessarily the golden path experience that you are primarily designing around.

106
00:06:18,243 --> 00:06:23,245
So I mean, I think, yes, engineering limitations can be a bit of an issue.

107
00:06:23,285 --> 00:06:30,928
But I think the bigger thing to think about for narrative and again, for any design department is just what is the level of freedom you're offering players?

108
00:06:31,748 --> 00:06:41,672
You know, what sort of gameplay tools do we have as designers and are we offering players just to make sure that the experience that you're trying to set up actually plays well with the game that you're making?

109
00:06:43,040 --> 00:06:50,747
Right on. Kirstie Logan Fowler is asking a question that I would consider one of the most loaded questions I hear from narrative folks, but we're going to go for it.

110
00:06:51,107 --> 00:07:00,576
What kind of structure do you use? Heroes Journey, 3-act structure, 5-act structure, and does it differ between games and different types of games? I just heard a bunch of knives being unchiefed somewhere.

111
00:07:01,977 --> 00:07:02,337
Yeah.

112
00:07:03,455 --> 00:07:09,097
I'm not really, I don't know, I'm not a huge believer in any one of those structures being like,

113
00:07:09,518 --> 00:07:12,919
the right way to tell stories, the right way to tell game stories.

114
00:07:14,680 --> 00:07:19,302
The way I look at tools like that is, if it is a useful framework for you to think in,

115
00:07:19,562 --> 00:07:24,064
and for you to think about story and pacing and escalation and character arcs,

116
00:07:24,404 --> 00:07:29,887
then go ahead and use it. But I think that, you know, when you get into writing a

117
00:07:31,329 --> 00:07:37,893
Writing a story to fit a formula rather than using a framework to help you create and pace your story,

118
00:07:37,913 --> 00:07:44,577
I think you're putting the cart before the horse. We do tend to write a lot of our story overviews

119
00:07:44,637 --> 00:07:49,420
and our story briefs with three-act structure. I've definitely done that and I've seen a number

120
00:07:49,440 --> 00:07:54,242
of other people at Obsidian use three or even five-act structure. But again, it's less about

121
00:07:54,302 --> 00:07:59,185
saying, oh, we have to follow this very rigid formula around our acts and more just

122
00:08:00,130 --> 00:08:06,653
Let's think about the phases and the developments and the major beats that players are going to go through.

123
00:08:07,113 --> 00:08:10,874
And what environment is the player in now?

124
00:08:10,994 --> 00:08:12,975
What are the big problems in front of them?

125
00:08:13,015 --> 00:08:17,837
What are we trying to pull them towards at each of these different phases of the story?

126
00:08:20,719 --> 00:08:25,581
With a more open world game, with something where you're offering players lots of freedom in what they do and how they explore.

127
00:08:25,601 --> 00:08:32,764
Again, you have to keep in mind, they may not follow the story beats the way you are intending them to.

128
00:08:33,645 --> 00:08:36,446
So again, you cannot, you can't necessarily engineer.

129
00:08:37,054 --> 00:08:41,277
The perfect 3X structure for like every player who goes through Prim to get to New Vegas

130
00:08:41,417 --> 00:08:45,399
and also every player who fights through, you know, the Death Claws on the other side

131
00:08:45,459 --> 00:08:46,000
to get there.

132
00:08:46,560 --> 00:08:50,943
But you do have to understand that players may choose that other experience and they

133
00:08:50,963 --> 00:08:55,986
still expect to have a good time even if they understand that they're, you know, by choice

134
00:08:56,466 --> 00:08:59,068
skipping out on some of the other content you've laid in front of them.

135
00:08:59,760 --> 00:09:02,102
Mm-hmm. I'm going to roll two questions together.

136
00:09:02,122 --> 00:09:05,285
Noah Denny asks, how would you suggest a high school student

137
00:09:05,305 --> 00:09:07,066
to get a career in the video game industry?

138
00:09:07,447 --> 00:09:10,389
Connor McClaskey is also asking, what is the number one mistake

139
00:09:10,409 --> 00:09:12,991
you see beginners who want to get into a narrative design career make?

140
00:09:13,312 --> 00:09:15,153
Those are both kind of career starting questions.

141
00:09:15,213 --> 00:09:16,975
I figured I would throw them both in the pool at once.

142
00:09:17,335 --> 00:09:20,978
So you could formulate the answer that you see covers that topic.

143
00:09:21,798 --> 00:09:24,421
Yeah, I'd say for getting into the games industry,

144
00:09:26,477 --> 00:09:28,839
However you can, which isn't super helpful.

145
00:09:30,380 --> 00:09:37,126
And the thing is, we're such a young industry, and it is developing so quickly that even though

146
00:09:37,146 --> 00:09:44,413
I joined a little more than seven years ago, my experience was I applied to an online opening,

147
00:09:45,874 --> 00:09:48,436
interviewed, did a narrative test, and got the job.

148
00:09:51,813 --> 00:09:54,175
That is certainly not how many of my colleagues have gotten in.

149
00:09:54,575 --> 00:09:56,996
Many people have gotten in through other studios

150
00:09:57,036 --> 00:09:59,077
where they garnered other experience.

151
00:09:59,137 --> 00:10:01,579
Or if they wanted to get into narrative design

152
00:10:01,679 --> 00:10:04,560
or a different role, they maybe started in something else.

153
00:10:05,040 --> 00:10:08,102
Like QA is a common entry point for a lot of people.

154
00:10:08,162 --> 00:10:11,524
But honestly, if you can get into another design role,

155
00:10:11,564 --> 00:10:14,105
that's often one of the most narrative adjacent

156
00:10:14,265 --> 00:10:15,926
if you want to get some of that experience.

157
00:10:15,946 --> 00:10:17,807
So I think...

158
00:10:21,422 --> 00:10:29,905
Understand which of those roles you're targeting, but be open to adjacent roles that may still

159
00:10:29,965 --> 00:10:36,848
allow you to get more experience, and also allow you to show that you are a capable person who can

160
00:10:37,348 --> 00:10:44,811
learn and address challenges as they come at you. It's obviously very important. As far as mistakes,

161
00:10:46,418 --> 00:10:51,041
I think one thing is just not honing writing fundamentals enough.

162
00:10:52,102 --> 00:10:57,686
I think fortunately, we're getting to a point where game narrative and narrative design

163
00:10:57,866 --> 00:10:57,926
is...

164
00:10:58,635 --> 00:11:04,920
You know, becoming enough of an established discipline that you don't hear as much anymore like, oh, well, it's good enough for games.

165
00:11:05,180 --> 00:11:07,822
Like, you know, no, we expect quality.

166
00:11:09,143 --> 00:11:21,112
And so, you know, honestly, just basic sentence level, you know, being able to write strong, error free dialogue that is mechanically correct, that conveys a sense of character that.

167
00:11:21,829 --> 00:11:24,813
that implies things without over-explaining them,

168
00:11:25,354 --> 00:11:28,860
and also, honestly, that gives players- well, for an RPG in particular.

169
00:11:29,223 --> 00:11:33,567
that gives players sort of hooks to establish their own role

170
00:11:33,647 --> 00:11:34,788
and involvement around.

171
00:11:34,928 --> 00:11:37,630
Like, you know, the least interesting conversations

172
00:11:37,710 --> 00:11:41,253
in a lot of RPGs are the ones where an NPC is telling you

173
00:11:41,293 --> 00:11:44,715
their very detailed backstory and your options are basically,

174
00:11:44,835 --> 00:11:46,476
uh-huh, listen, go on, yes.

175
00:11:46,957 --> 00:11:50,179
You know, the more interesting ones, I think of like improv,

176
00:11:50,219 --> 00:11:52,641
where as a player, you're presented with a scenario

177
00:11:52,761 --> 00:11:55,984
or confrontation or, you know, a question of some kind

178
00:11:56,124 --> 00:11:57,885
and you are interacting with this other NPC.

179
00:11:59,790 --> 00:12:04,197
And you're sort of expressing yourself as a character in this world through your interaction with them.

180
00:12:06,318 --> 00:12:10,942
Gotcha. When you brought up that example of the character reading backstory and you're

181
00:12:10,962 --> 00:12:16,847
and the only examples are, tell me more, I thought of that My Dinner with Andre interactive

182
00:12:16,867 --> 00:12:21,291
game joke from The Simpsons from like the 90s or something and how they beat Telltale to that

183
00:12:21,331 --> 00:12:26,616
format. Anyway, that's too deep of a joke. Jung Shang Lin would like to know, in the outer worlds

184
00:12:26,676 --> 00:12:31,740
is there any notable difference in terms of your approach to narrative design compared to Pillars

185
00:12:31,760 --> 00:12:32,401
of Eternity 1 and 2?

186
00:12:34,440 --> 00:13:00,951
Um, yes. So and some of this may be a little, maybe fairly micro. I mean, one big thing is in the Pillars games, you know, those were top down isometric games where you were very zoomed out from the player or from from the characters on the screen. And so, you know, that definitely limited what we could show happening on screen. But it also meant that we had a bit more freedom to use descriptive prose to describe someone's

187
00:13:01,559 --> 00:13:07,243
Gesture, expression, describe kind of what they're doing within like a believable sort of bubble around them.

188
00:13:08,803 --> 00:13:20,150
With The Outer Worlds, you know, obviously we want to, you know, write dialogue and then use, you know, gestures and facial animations to show those shifts in emotion and to show characters actually

189
00:13:20,580 --> 00:13:26,144
doing things in the world. Which, you know, in some ways, and maybe this is also because,

190
00:13:26,264 --> 00:13:30,587
you know, I come from a background writing novels and short stories, I did really miss that ability

191
00:13:30,627 --> 00:13:35,471
to write descriptive prose and to let that do some of, you know, some of the storytelling,

192
00:13:35,491 --> 00:13:40,414
heavy lifting, and also just some of the, handle some of the emotional beats, you know, of someone

193
00:13:40,454 --> 00:13:46,218
who is saying one thing but emoting another. Because that's obviously very hard to do.

194
00:13:47,479 --> 00:13:51,721
You know, even with very, you know, unless you're, you know, performance capturing everything.

195
00:13:52,782 --> 00:13:57,705
So that was one big difference. And I think the other was just sort of the understanding,

196
00:13:57,745 --> 00:14:03,488
obviously, of who the player is and what, what sort of range of characterizations we're letting

197
00:14:03,528 --> 00:14:09,291
them embody in the world. Again, pillars drawing a bit more from tabletop. We tried to widen that

198
00:14:09,351 --> 00:14:14,194
range a bit and we say, you know, you are the watcher and this is the context for which you

199
00:14:14,214 --> 00:14:14,414
have.

200
00:14:14,870 --> 00:14:20,672
Unique insight and abilities in this world and, you know, why you can help people solve these problems that they have.

201
00:14:21,872 --> 00:14:24,352
But, you know, again, trying to follow that tabletop formula.

202
00:14:25,013 --> 00:14:28,993
We have a variety of dispositions and a variety of, you know, skills.

203
00:14:29,134 --> 00:14:35,615
And so we want to make sure that however you are sort of building yourself accordingly, that you feel you can express that character.

204
00:14:36,335 --> 00:14:41,396
For The Outer Worlds, we still wanted to take a pretty light touch in terms of assuming who the player character is.

205
00:14:42,897 --> 00:14:57,559
You know, as an outsider, they don't actually have a role, you know, like the Watcher that gives them a really, really unique skill set, except that they are an outsider to a world where they can sort of see the absurdity of it just because they are not of it.

206
00:14:59,839 --> 00:15:04,841
But yeah, you know, one of the big models for who the player character is in that world was

207
00:15:04,941 --> 00:15:11,602
Mal Reynolds from Firefly. You know, the idea of someone who's not a saint, not a villain,

208
00:15:12,583 --> 00:15:19,705
someone with sort of a morally gray spectrum who can embody either end or some range in between

209
00:15:19,845 --> 00:15:20,945
as the player wants to.

210
00:15:23,311 --> 00:15:27,918
Ellen Ducarpe asks one of my favorite questions in here, which is, as a narrative designer,

