00:17:42,354 --> 00:17:49,797
I think where that character started is just wanting to give her a very authentic and sort

248
00:17:49,817 --> 00:17:52,198
of emotionally resonant experience.

249
00:17:52,218 --> 00:17:58,380
Because Parvati's arc is about, you know, she's from this small town and she gets out

250
00:17:58,400 --> 00:18:01,101
of Edgewater and gets to finally see the rest of the galaxy.

251
00:18:01,161 --> 00:18:03,742
And part of what makes her so interesting is that...

252
00:18:04,205 --> 00:18:11,210
She's so kind and pure and good in a world that is corrupt and cruel and nasty.

253
00:18:11,810 --> 00:18:20,216
And there's this, you know, I certainly, you know, when I first played those early builds, I was like, well, how is this character going to react, you know, when she gets out there?

254
00:18:20,276 --> 00:18:27,741
And also, how do we make her how do we make her feel like she is part of the same world when she is so clearly different from it?

255
00:18:28,401 --> 00:18:30,523
So, you know, I think just.

256
00:18:31,418 --> 00:18:39,063
Giving her a story and a quest that related to her sort of embracing and accepting more of who she is,

257
00:18:39,804 --> 00:18:46,268
that led her to an authentic and emotionally fulfilling relationship. Again, even in a world

258
00:18:46,328 --> 00:18:55,694
that does not seem to place a lot of value on those. I don't recall any specific discussion

259
00:18:55,734 --> 00:18:59,997
about her as an asexual character. It's like, oh, should we? No, it's like,

