00:19:00,953 --> 00:19:03,915
This is who the character is and this is the story we're telling about her.

261
00:19:04,835 --> 00:19:06,016
And so we just want to tell it well.

262
00:19:07,736 --> 00:19:15,059
Getting off topic from Adderall's characters, Stephen Morosola would like to know, how do

263
00:19:15,099 --> 00:19:19,341
you handle or deal with writer's block if you or anyone on the writing team has experienced

264
00:19:19,401 --> 00:19:20,182
it during development?

265
00:19:22,122 --> 00:19:27,245
Well, so one thing, sometimes honestly it helps just to move on to a different task

266
00:19:27,305 --> 00:19:29,145
or a different piece of content if you can.

267
00:19:29,165 --> 00:19:30,486
I know I have a tendency to try to.

268
00:19:30,993 --> 00:19:34,035
You know, kind of bang my head against a wall trying to solve one problem.

269
00:19:34,796 --> 00:19:38,539
When sometimes the best thing to do is just step back from it and let those details marinate in

270
00:19:38,559 --> 00:19:43,904
the back of your mind as you're doing something else. Another technique I like to use, especially

271
00:19:43,924 --> 00:19:49,368
if I really do need to get some quest or character writing done, is even if I'm having writer's block

272
00:19:49,468 --> 00:19:54,372
around, you know, who that character is, what makes the conversation with the player character

273
00:19:54,432 --> 00:20:00,457
interesting and engaging, I generally at least know how and where the conversation begins.

274
00:20:01,470 --> 00:20:03,471
And where we need to get the player by the end of it.

275
00:20:04,031 --> 00:20:17,217
And so sometimes I like to do something that I think of as a rough pass, which is it's, you know, it's not, it's not purely placeholder text as in, you know, Sanjar says this or Sanjar tells player to go here.

276
00:20:17,717 --> 00:20:18,837
It's, you know, it's.

277
00:20:19,350 --> 00:20:24,592
It's just sort of, it's something between that and, you know, an actual invoice writing pass.

278
00:20:24,632 --> 00:20:28,813
And it's just, it's kind of, it's what other writers I think talk about when they say turning

279
00:20:28,873 --> 00:20:32,333
off your inner editor, where it's like, this doesn't have to be good, this doesn't have to

280
00:20:32,353 --> 00:20:38,815
be final, this just has to let me explore a way to get from A to B without worrying that I'm setting

281
00:20:38,875 --> 00:20:42,896
anything in stone and without worrying that this is what, you know, people are going to review

282
00:20:43,076 --> 00:20:45,676
in another week. And sometimes, honestly, just

283
00:20:46,417 --> 00:20:50,120
Getting that structure out there lets me return to it later and then see,

284
00:20:50,480 --> 00:20:53,943
oh, well, here's some clear beats and arcs and moments that are happening,

285
00:20:54,303 --> 00:20:58,467
you know, even in this, you know, roughed out version that I can build on and have fun with.

286
00:20:58,527 --> 00:21:03,071
Or, oh, okay, well, now that the work of sort of structuring this out at a high level is done,

287
00:21:03,751 --> 00:21:07,774
now I feel like I have a bit more room to think and play with what makes it fun.

288
00:21:09,828 --> 00:21:24,137
Gotcha. Philip and Icek would like to know when a concept of a game is created at the very beginning, before, or during pre-production, what questions do you usually need answered to establish the pillars or main points for the core game idea?

