00:24:11,024 --> 00:24:13,525
a pretty wide latitude in who they are in the world.

339
00:24:13,745 --> 00:24:16,527
So with that in mind, I think the biggest,

340
00:24:17,403 --> 00:24:20,585
The biggest difference is just understanding who the protagonist is.

341
00:24:21,586 --> 00:24:25,108
You know, in a novel or any other piece of prose fiction, obviously you have

342
00:24:26,069 --> 00:24:29,792
a very carefully choreographed arc that you're sending that main character on.

343
00:24:30,112 --> 00:24:31,253
You know the beats they're going to hit.

344
00:24:31,293 --> 00:24:32,754
You know how they're going to react to them.

345
00:24:33,234 --> 00:24:37,117
And you were telling a story around that when you were writing an RPG

346
00:24:37,177 --> 00:24:39,419
like Pillars of Eternity or like The Outer Worlds.

347
00:24:40,764 --> 00:24:45,969
You have beats that you know the player is going to hit, but you want to offer the player some room

348
00:24:46,190 --> 00:24:49,853
in expressing how they feel about those beats and how they want to react to them.

349
00:24:50,974 --> 00:24:56,220
And so there's, it's actually pretty exciting, like it's a lot of fun to look at a particular

350
00:24:56,240 --> 00:24:59,823
moment and think, well, this is how I feel about it, but how might someone else feel about it?

